Why it is harder for women to save for retirement
Only 50pc of women in their 30s work full–time and almost 20pc prioritise financially supporting their children above saving for retirement.
Gary and Laura Lurcock prefer the flexibility of saving into a joint cash account. By Nicole Blackmore
8:07AM GMT 20 Nov 2013
Follow Comments
Most people struggle to put enough money away to fund a comfortable retirement – but the challenge is particularly difficult for women who take time out of work to raise a family. Research suggests that only 50pc of women in their 30s work full–time, compared with 81pc of men of the same age. Whether taking an extended career break or returning to work parttime, mothers will usually see their income reduce significantly. Combined with the added costs of raising a family, pensions are often relegated to the bottom of the priority list. Almost 20pc of women in their thirties prioritise financially supporting their children above saving for retirement, according to this year's Scottish Widows "Women and Pensions" Report. And 21pc of women in this age group expect to rely on their partner's income for retirement, according to the annual study. This can be a risky move – especially considering the rising divorce rate among couples in their fifties and sixties. There are steps women can take to boost their chances of a comfortable retirement. Your Money collected tips from financial planners on Unbiased.co.uk, the directory of advice firms, to help women plan. Related Articles
Tax cut offers workers £11,000 'pension boost’
21 Nov 2013
Cameron's broken promise to savers costs £68bn
18 Nov 2013
Scottish Widows 'moves billions to dud funds'
18 Nov 2013
Minister: insurers make 'excess profit' from pension savers
18 Nov 2013
How will new hybrid pensions affect younger workers?
11 Nov 2013
Maternity leave
Legislation requires employer and employee pension contributions to continue while a woman is on paid maternity leave. The length of paid leave will vary between companies but the statutory minimum is up to 39 weeks. Thanks to compound interest, any money saved into a pension in your twenties or thirties will work hard over the years to grow your retirement income. So continuing saving even a small amount can have a significant impact. Women who take longer than 12 months off work can be forced to leave the pension scheme – check with your employer. Protect your state pension
The new flat–rate state pension will be worth approximately £144 a week from 2016. Anyone with 35 years of qualifying National Insurance contributions will qualify for this. Stephen Womack, an adviser at David Williams Chartered Financial Planners, said women must not underestimate the importance of building up entitlement. "It would cost a woman aged 66 approximately £195,000 to buy that level of index–linked pension with their own savings," he said. Women who take time out of employment should continue building credits. This happens automatically if a family claims child benefit. It is worth registering even if one partner earns an annual salary of £60,000 or more and you must repay the benefit at the end of the tax year. Pension credits stop when the youngest child reaches 12 years of age, so if you haven't gone back into work by then, consider making voluntary National Insurance contributions. Save – but not necessarily into a pension
Most stay–at–home mothers will be a non or basic–rate taxpayer, so to put additional money into a pension would offer limited tax benefits. However, savers benefit from a 20pc tax relief boost on the first £2,880 of pension contributions per tax year, regardless of whether income is earned, turning the sum into £3,600. The same limits apply if someone else, such as a partner, makes contributions on your behalf. An Isa is often a better option. You can invest up to £11,520 in an Isa during this tax year – which at £960 a month is often sufficient – and your money grows tax–free. You can access the cash if you need, but be careful not to dip too deep into retirement savings. Back at work, you could move the money into a pension to generate tax relief – a good idea for women who pay higher–rate tax. Should you leave the company, consider transferring the pension to a self–invested personal pension (Sipp), which has greater investment control. However, check for valuable benefits offered by your company first, such as life cover or guaranteed payout rates on annuities. Don't rely solely on your partner's pension
Unfortunately, marriages do break down – around 42pc end in divorce across England, according to the Office for National Statistics. Pensions are frequently undervalued in divorce settlements, so make sure you have separate provision. Don't disregard saving as a couple, though – if the husband or partner is a higher–rate taxpayer or his employer will match some or all of any contribution he makes to his company scheme, it could be worthwhile using his scheme. 'It's hard to save when you've just had a baby'
Laura Lurcock, 28, is on maternity leave from her role as an administrator at Brighton & Hove council. She had her son, Joshua, four and a half months ago and plans to take 12 months' maternity leave before returning to work part–time. Mrs Lurcock has a company pension scheme, so her contributions will continue from her maternity pay. Her husband, Gary, 32, an operations manager, does not currently have a workplace pension. Mrs Lurcock said: "We decided to save as much as we can at the end of every month into a joint savings account and part of that is for our retirement. It's difficult to put much away because there are so many expenses that you just don't expect when you have a baby. "We like the flexibility of a savings account and the easy access to our money that an online cash account gives us."
