Catherine Zeta Jones 'received treatment for manic depression'
Catherine Zeta Jones on Wednesday revealed that she sought treatment for manic depression after struggling to cope with the stress of husband Michael Douglas's battle with throat cancer. Michael Douglas had chemotherapy for throat cancer last year but said in January that his tumour had gone after six months of intensive treatment Photo: AFP/GETTY	By Alex Spillius, Washington
11:00PM BST 13 Apr 2011
Follow Comments
The 41-year-old Welsh actor reportedly checked into a £770-a-day clinic in Connecticut for five days earlier this month. "After dealing with the stress of the past year, Catherine made the decision to check in to a mental health facility for a brief stay to treat her Bipolar II Disorder," said publicist Cece Yorke said in a statement. "She's feeling great and looking forward to starting work this week on her two upcoming films," she said. Bipolar disorder is the technical term for manic depression, and involves wild mood swings from high to low, though in Bipolar II the "up" moods never reach full mania. A friend told America's People magazine: "There's no question it's been a stressful year. Catherine has had deal with Michael's illness and that's been hard. She went in for a few days because she's about to start working, and wanted to make sure she's in top form, which she is."
