Some patients have to rely on requests for cataract surgery and some therapies backed by the National Institute for Health and Clinical Excellence such as diabetes education and insulin pumps, GP found. A Department of Health spokesman said: “It is unacceptable for the NHS to impose blanket bans for treatment on the basis of cost.”
A report into the impact of the Blair government’s NHS reforms has revealed the proportion of patients seeing their local NHS trust has fallen significantly, while those referred to privately-owned centres has risen. The study by the Institute for Fiscal Studies found that in 2010/11, private sector treatment had gone from a “negligible presence” in outpatient care to accounting for 3.5 per cent – almost half a million – of all first appointments. News
