Christmas travel guide
Cruising for Christmas Carol concerts, Nativity plays, visits from Santa – cruise ships really go to town at Christmas, says Sara Macefield. Image 1 of 4	P and O cruise ship in the Caribbean, Cruising for Christmas Image 1 of 4	Father Christmas on board a Fred Olsen cruise ship, Cruising for Christmas Image 1 of 4	Many cruise ships, such as Fred Olsen, have a grotto on board during the festive period Image 1 of 4	For those seeking a child-free festive period, P and O is offering a 15-night adult-only cruise through the Mexican Riviera 3:05PM GMT 02 Feb 2008
Comments
Cruise lines do things in more than usually fine style at Christmas. Many spend thousands of pounds transforming their ships into Yuletide fun palaces, with huge Christmas trees, garlands, wreaths, ornate sleighs and handcrafted ornaments. Crystal Cruises, for example, lavishes around £50,000 on seasonal decorations for each of its ships, while P&O Cruises even flies out professional decorators to transform its Caribbean cruises. "It's a big operation for us," says the company's marketing spokeman, Philip Price. "It's not just a question of the captain going around and sticking up bits of holly."
And this is just for starters. Then there are the carol concerts, choirs, Nativity plays and Christmas Day church services. On some ships, Santa pops in with presents for every passenger and on P&O's hugely popular child-friendly vessels he even has his own grotto, complete with a gingerbread village. So which cruise? Experienced cruisers tend to look for the onboard atmosphere when it comes to choosing their Christmas trip, but first-timers often opt for fly-cruises in the Caribbean or other warm climates. Related Articles
River cruise by day, then play the city markets
08 Oct 2007
Then there's the question of whether to spend just a week away over Christmas or New Year, or go the whole hog and take a two-week trip over both. To help you choose, here is my selection of festive cruises that still have availability. Prices are per person and based on two people sharing, unless otherwise stated. Norway Hurtigruten (020 8846 2666; www.hurtigruten.co.uk), the Norwegian cruise specialist, lets you spend Christmas off the Norwegian coast on a five-day trip from Tromso to Bergen. The trip, which departs on December 22, visits the dramatic Lofoten Islands, where you can take a dog-sledding tour and observe a traditional fishing community. The voyage also offers a good chance of seeing the Northern Lights, as well close-up views of some of Europe's most spectacular coastline. The cost is from £775, including half board on the ship, transfers and flights from Heathrow. The Mediterranean MSC Cruises (0870 850 4883; www.msccruises.co.uk) has a 12-day Mediterranean fly-cruise from Genoa on December 18 from £799, including flights. The cruise, aboard MSC Musica, calls at Ajaccio, Malta, Rhodes, Egypt, Tripoli, Messina and Naples before returning to Genoa. The Canaries Fred Olsen cruises (01473 742424; www.fredolsencruises.co.uk) offers a 16-night Christmas and New Year to the Canary Islands aboard Black Watch, departing Dover on December 20. The first ports of call – La Coruña in Spain and Tangier in Morocco – allow for last-minute Christmas shopping before the ship docks at Arrecife, in Lanzarote, on Boxing Day. Subsequent stops include Las Palmas in Gran Canaria, Santa Cruz, Tenerife, San Sebastián in La Gomera and Santa Cruz, La Palma. New Year's Eve is spent in Funchal, Madeira, where guests welcome in the year with a fireworks display. Prices start at £1,866, which includes a 40 per cent discount. Travelscope (0844 412 4444; www.travelscope.co.uk) still has cabins on its 15-day Christmas and New Year "Sunshine Cruise" departing Falmouth on December 21 and visiting seven ports, including Vigo, Gibraltar on Christmas Day, Casablanca on Boxing Day and Funchal, Madeira, on New Year's Eve. Prices start at £899. The Caribbean Carnival Cruises (020 7940 4466; www.carnivalcruise.co.uk) still has space on a seven-night sailing from Miami on December 22 to the Eastern Caribbean. The cruise calls at Half Moon Cay, a private island in the Bahamas, St Thomas in the US Virgin Islands, San Juan, Puerto Rico and Grand Turk in the Turks and Caicos islands. The cruise costs just £449, but you need to organise your own flights to Florida. Ocean Village (0845 358 5000; www.oceanvillageholidays.co.uk) is a casual cruise line, with laid-back trips where you could spend the festive season swimming with dolphins or roaring around on Harley-Davidson motorbikes. The company's "Coral & Calypso" seven-night sailing (from £1,179) departs Barbados on December 19, visiting Tortola, St Maarten, St Kitts, Antigua and Dominica. Passengers wanting a longer cruise can add a second sailing, the one-week "Sugar & Spice" voyage, which follows directly afterwards on December 26 and follows a different route. The price for the combined 14-night cruise is from £1,749, including return flights to Barbados. Royal Caribbean cruises (0845 165 8330; www.royalcaribbean.co.uk) is offering (among other things) an eggnog party, carol singing, Midnight Mass and a Christmas talent show on its 14-night Southern Caribbean fly-cruise on December 22. The cost is from £2,212, including flights and a one-night hotel stay. The 12-night cruise sails from New York for St Maarten, Antigua, Dominica, Barbados, St Kitts, St Thomas and Puerto Rico before returning to New York. Saga Cruises (0800 505030; www.saga.co.uk) has an option for customers wanting to avoid the airport crush of the festive getaway: drive to Southampton and step aboard the Saga Rose for a 30-night voyage, costing from £4,229, which departs December 6 and calls at the Azores before reaching the Caribbean, where stops include Tobago, Grenada, St Lucia and Antigua before returning to the UK via Madeira. SeaDream Yacht Club (0800 783 1373; www.seadream.com) is offering Christmas and New Year sailings on its SeaDream I luxury yacht. The Christmas voyage departs San Juan in Puerto Rico and calls at the uninhabited island of Culebrita, Esperanza – famous for its bioluminescent waters – and the Caribbean islands of St John, St Martin, St Barts, Virgin Gorda and Jost Van Dyke – before returning to Puerto Rico. The cruise-only price is from $5,112 (£2,560). The New Year sailing follows a similar path and costs from $5,433 (£2,720), cruise only. Ascension Island The Royal Mail Ship St Helena (020 7575 6480; www.rms-st-helena.com) lets you really get away from it all on a 128-berth boat that serves the remote South Atlantic outposts of Ascension Island and St Helena. Passengers can join the ship on December 21, when it departs Ascension Island for a three-night voyage to St Helena and then travels on to Walvis Bay in Namibia, where it arrives on December 29. This cruise costs from £452, but for an extra £160 passengers can sail from here to Cape Town, arriving on New Year's Day. Flights are not included. The US and Mexico Crystal Cruises (020 7287 9040; www.crystalcruises.com) still has availability on a 16-night fly-cruise from Los Angeles with calls at San Diego and Cabo San Lucas, before sailing to the Mexican resorts of Acapulco, Zihuatanejo, Puerto Vallarta, Mazatlan and La Paz (returning to Los Angeles). Prices start at £5,243 and include flights, an overnight stay in Los Angeles pre-cruise and transfers. On the 14-night sailing, basic gratuities and soft drinks are also included. Norwegian Cruise Line (0845 658 8010; www.ncl.co.uk) is offering a heady combination of New York and the Caribbean on one-week cruises departing the Big Apple on December 19 and 26. The line's newest ship, Norwegian Gem, cruises the Atlantic before calling at Port Canaveral in Florida (for Orlando), Key West and Great Stirrup Cay, NCL's private island in the Bahamas. It then returns to New York. The 11-night package, which includes three nights' room-only in New York, costs from £1,589, flights included. P&O Cruises (0845 678 0014; www.pocruises.com) offers those wanting a child-free festive season a trip through the Mexican Riviera on adult-only ship Arcadia. The 15-night fly-cruise departs on December 14 from Barbados, sailing through the Caribbean with calls at islands including Grenada, Bonaire and Aruba, before heading southwards along the coast of Latin America. Christmas Day is spent at sea between Fuerte Amador in Panama and Puerto Quetzal in Guatemala before the ship calls at Huatulco in Mexico and finishes in the Mexican resort of Acapulco. It costs from £1,898. The Red Sea Thomson Cruises (0870 165 0079; www.thomson.co.uk) has an escape to the warm waters of the Red Sea for a one-week Christmas cruise. Passengers join the ship in the Egyptian resort of Sharm el Sheikh and sail to Port Sokhna, for excursions to Cairo. The next stop is Safaga, where customers can visit the beach resort of Hurghada or the ancient city of Luxor and the Valley of the Kings. The ship then sails to Jordan, where passengers are able to explore Petra. The cruise costs from £829, including flights. The Indian Ocean Costa Cruises (020 7940 4499; www.costacruises.co.uk) has knocked £530 off the price of its 14-night Christmas sailing around the Indian Ocean. The voyage now starts at £2,269, including flights, and departs on December 22 from Port Louis on Mauritius. The Costa Marina sails for Mahe in the Seychelles and on to Mombasa, Mayotte in the Comoro Islands, Madagascar, St Denis and Réunion Island before returning to St Louis. Indian Ocean Cruises (0800 032 7020; www.indianoceancruises.net) lets you celebrate Christmas on the ancient spice route along India's Malabar Coast. The company's two-week cruise departs Goa on December 15, spending Christmas Day in Trivandrum, India, before following the south coast to the virtually uninhabited Lakshadweep islands in the Indian Ocean and calling at Sri Lanka's capital Colombo. The sailing costs from £940, representing a discount of more than £300 on the normal price. Flights are not included. The Antipodes Holland America Line (0845 351 0557; www.hollandamerica.co.uk) allows passengers an Australasian touch to their festive celebrations with a 16-night cruise from Sydney on December 20. The ships then calls at Melbourne, Tasmania, Milford Sound, Dunedin, Christchurch, Picton, Wellington, Napier and Tauranga before finishing in Auckland. It costs from £1,479, excluding flights. Silversea Cruises (0844 770 9030; www.silversea.com) is offering a 16-night sailing of Australasia from Singapore on December 20, with calls that include Kura Kura, Darwin, Cairns, the Whitsunday Islands, and Brisbane before finishing in Sydney on January 5. The cruise's guest speaker will be journalist and former BBC newsreader Michael Buerk. Prices start at £6,245, excluding flights. Star Cruises (0845 260 8880; www.starcruises.com) still has cabins on its 15-night Christmas special from Brisbane to Fremantle, departing December 11, calling at the Whitsunday Islands, Cairns, Townsville, Milne Bay in Papua New Guinea and Darwin. The cruise-only price starts at £1,721. The Antarctic Voyages of Discovery (01444 462150; www.voyagesofdiscovery.com) lets you see in the New Year in the Antarctic on a 20-day adventure to the Antarctic Peninsula and South Georgia. The cruise starts on December 21 with flights to Buenos Aires, where passengers join the ship. Ports of call include Ushuaia, Port Stanley in the Falklands, Coronation Island, Antarctic Sound, Hope Bay and Half Moon Island. Prices are from £2,995, including flights, a two-night hotel stay in Buenos Aires with breakfast, onboard lectures and tips. Greek Island cruise for all the family Music cruise in the Mediterranean Christmas travel guide Christmas travel guide
