In a world without alcohol, we'd have fewer murders, rapes, assaults, STDs, unwanted pregnancies, road deaths, twisted ankles, shoot-ups on submarines, tragic rock-star deaths, cases of liver cancer, student clubs, kebab shops, karaoke nights, A&E admissions, stolen street signs, Pogues songs, paparazzi scoops, random bruises, dinner parties, comedians, corner shops, love bites, stag dos, silent discos, festivals, New Year's Resolutions, friends, regrets and stories to tell our grandchildren.
Not only would year-round abstinence pack a full-force sucker punch to restaurants, theatres, working men’s clubs, opera houses, cabarets, speed-dating events, sports grounds, casinos, nightclubs, music and comedy venues – all of which rely, to a greater or lesser extent, on booze sales to remain profitable – but it would also spell the death knell for that laudable British institution: the pub.
Now I’ve lived in Germany, the States and Japan, and travelled about a fair bit, and I have yet to encounter anything remotely approximating a decent British boozer. Yes, Berliners can order beer in Maccy Ds, and New Yorkers can opt for bottomless mimosas with their weekend brunches, but they don’t generally hang out in drinking dens during the day, unless they’re dating a bar-person or self-defined as an alcoholic. For years Starbucks has been busting a gut to market itself as the ‘third place’ – a cosy, social space between work and home. It might as well have saved itself a lot of corporate bother. We’ve already got a ‘third place’: somewhere to catch up with friend, kick back by an open fire, or pick a fight with that tosser who’s looking at you funny.
For now we do, anyway.
Eighteen pubs a week are shutting their doors and/or being transformed into Sainsbury’s Locals. For this we can thank to beer tax, the credit crunch and, presumably, some of them being a bit shit. In London, where we have an embarrassment of both decent and grotty boozers, it’s hard to feel the full impact of this pub blight. But head out to the sticks (by which I mean anywhere outside of Zone 3) and it’s easy enough to find pretty villages and boring housing estates where the one local pub sits boarded up and abandoned. This is a damn shame – particularly when you’ve been on a long walk to clear your hangover, and you’re bursting for the toilet and a decent pint of cider. Which is why I’m still supporting my local, despite being perched resentfully on the old sober wagon.
Given last night’s performance, though, they might not be as grateful as you’d imagine.
I'm on my feet. My voice is raised. I might even have resorted to Angry Pointy Finger. My face hasn't been this flushed since I watched three Ryan Gosling movies back-to-back. The punters at the next table are craning their necks to look. The mates who have just joined us shuffle awkwardly. I'm almost, sort of, kind of making a scene - starting a punch-up in a brew pub.
And it's all because of Fentimans ginger beer.
Now, I'm generally more a lover than a fighter. As a middle child, I'm usually self-designated keeper of the peace, steering the conversation into safer territory whenever it threatens to founder on the rocks of dissention or stray into the shallow waters of 'Was-it-me-or-was-that-a-little-bit-racist?'
But in my defence, this time the provocation was extreme.
"You know that's alcoholic, right?" Brighton Friend asks, nodding at my glass.
I narrowly avoid choking. "You're thinking of Crabbies."
"No, look!" She grabs the bottle and jabs her finger at label. "Look, it says 'brewed'."
I snatch the bottle back. "So? That doesn't mean anything..."
"It is! It's definitely got a trace of alcohol in it. Look, I'll get my glasses and show you ."
I hold the bottle about two inches from my eyes, desperately scanning the small print. "Ha! Nothing!" I plonk the bottle down, safely out of her reach.
I'm attempting a smile, but my heart is racing. It’s like the scene in the Josh Hartnett celibacy romp 40 Days & 40 Nights where his scheming ex sabotages his attempt at abstinence with the aid of a pair of handcuffs and Hartnett's own super-sized libido. For a second there it feels like Fentimans is the scheming ex, and I'm poor Hartnett, manacled to the bar
Which is when I got shouty and indignant. "Fine! Take my last remaining pleasure away! Just get me a... a sodding water then! Or are they brewing that now too?"
My friends exchange amused glances, pat me on the shoulder, and head off to the bar to get a round of proper drinks in.
